WEBVTT

00:03.699 --> 00:04.047
.

00:04.091 --> 00:05.918
- Don Kilbourne.

00:05.962 --> 00:08.182
You found a permanent home for
Lieutenant Jason Pelham.

00:08.225 --> 00:09.618
- I'm comfortable
with my decision.

00:09.661 --> 00:12.360
- Don't be.
You'll come to regret it.

00:12.403 --> 00:13.752
- Go ahead and
get set to tube him.

00:13.796 --> 00:17.234
- Don't you want to?
- You got this.

00:17.278 --> 00:19.019
You're a really talented
medic, Violet.

00:19.062 --> 00:21.847
And a lot of fun to be with.

00:21.891 --> 00:22.979
- Are we okay?

00:23.023 --> 00:24.502
- Do you still want
to marry me?

00:24.546 --> 00:28.289
- You are the one thing
that I am sure about, always.

00:28.332 --> 00:30.030
- You didn't
answer the question.

00:30.073 --> 00:31.727
[suspenseful music]

00:33.816 --> 00:35.600
[microwave beeps]

00:41.476 --> 00:43.478
- Mm.

00:43.521 --> 00:46.089
You're up early.

00:46.133 --> 00:48.874
- Just getting coffee going.
- Mm.

00:48.918 --> 00:51.877
[soft sentimental music]

00:51.921 --> 00:53.444
♪

00:53.488 --> 00:54.445
Hey.

01:00.451 --> 01:02.323
I meant what I said last night.

01:05.239 --> 01:06.718
I want to marry you.

01:08.372 --> 01:12.550
Yes, yes, a million times--
- I heard you.

01:12.594 --> 01:15.075
- Okay, good.

01:15.118 --> 01:16.728
And I'm not expecting that

01:16.772 --> 01:19.470
to make everything perfect
between us overnight.

01:19.514 --> 01:21.124
You know, I get that
I screwed up.

01:21.168 --> 01:23.039
And that I have to
earn your trust--

01:23.083 --> 01:24.214
- Stella.

01:25.607 --> 01:27.870
- Yeah?
- We're good.

01:31.134 --> 01:32.570
- Yeah, okay.

01:35.312 --> 01:37.271
I love you.

01:43.929 --> 01:46.149
- Welcome back, partner.
- How was the trip to Portland?

01:46.193 --> 01:47.846
- Never long enough
but so much fun.

01:47.890 --> 01:48.934
- Casey's doing well?

01:48.978 --> 01:50.588
- He is and the boys
are doing great.

01:50.632 --> 01:53.156
- How's he like his new post?
- So far so good.

01:53.200 --> 01:55.941
His firehouse responded to
a wild fire a few weeks back,

01:55.985 --> 01:58.422
which he said is
like playing a whole new sport.

01:58.466 --> 02:01.077
Oh, hey, who'd you end up
getting as a floater?

02:01.121 --> 02:02.948
- Actually, Hawkins filled in.

02:02.992 --> 02:04.776
- What?
- Yeah.

02:04.820 --> 02:07.605
Guess he was doing ride-alongs
and the schedules lined up.

02:07.649 --> 02:10.434
I can see why he rose up
the ranks so fast.

02:10.478 --> 02:12.697
He's impressive.
- Yeah, how so?

02:12.741 --> 02:14.569
- We had this
really intense call.

02:14.612 --> 02:16.527
We had to intubate a newborn

02:16.571 --> 02:18.747
and he was so calm
under pressure.

02:18.790 --> 02:20.183
- Don't want to be late
for the morning briefing.

02:20.227 --> 02:21.619
- Oh, sorry.

02:21.663 --> 02:22.925
We're really lucky to
have a chief like that.

02:22.968 --> 02:24.492
- Seriously.

02:29.018 --> 02:31.977
[rock music playing]

02:32.021 --> 02:38.506
♪

02:40.203 --> 02:42.336
- What's this?
- [shushes]

02:42.379 --> 02:44.338
- Hey, hey, hey,
wake up, Chicago.

02:44.381 --> 02:45.687
The Buzz Mann
is here spinning hits

02:45.730 --> 02:47.428
from morning rush
till lunch on Rush and--

02:47.471 --> 02:48.864
[whistle and crash]
Uh-oh.

02:48.907 --> 02:50.300
You know what
that sound means,

02:50.344 --> 02:52.868
it's time for
Hunt the Fugitive.

02:52.911 --> 02:54.565
Yahoo!

02:54.609 --> 02:57.829
10,000 cool, crisp American
dollars to the first listener

02:57.873 --> 02:59.266
who catches our fugitive
on the streets of Chicago.

02:59.309 --> 03:00.397
- Uh, okay.
- [shushes]

03:00.441 --> 03:01.659
- For a list of the rules

03:01.703 --> 03:03.487
visit Rock92ThePanther
website.

03:03.531 --> 03:05.489
And here we go
with our first clue.

03:05.533 --> 03:07.491
The fugitive is
gonna be barely dressed.

03:07.535 --> 03:10.668
And I mean B-E-A-R,
bear-ly dressed.

03:10.712 --> 03:13.323
Oh, that's a touchdown clue
if I ever heard one.

03:13.367 --> 03:14.977
Okay, super-sleuths,
you heard it.

03:15.020 --> 03:17.240
Keep it right here on Rock92
for more clues.

03:17.284 --> 03:19.155
And now--

03:19.199 --> 03:21.462
- So, let me see if I follow.

03:21.505 --> 03:25.509
92ThePanther is having
a contest where you have to

03:25.553 --> 03:29.687
"find the fugitive" and
if you do, you get $10,000.

03:29.731 --> 03:34.301
- Not you, us, together.
That's how you win this thing.

03:34.344 --> 03:36.433
All right, team up.
Spread the wealth.

03:36.477 --> 03:38.957
- In.
- Why not?

03:39.001 --> 03:40.263
- Yeah, sure.

03:40.307 --> 03:41.438
- Hey, how often
do they give out clues?

03:41.482 --> 03:43.484
- Every day,
10:00, 2:00, and 4:00.

03:43.527 --> 03:45.703
- And in the meantime,
the fugitive roams the streets

03:45.747 --> 03:47.792
of Chicago just waiting
for someone to catch them?

03:47.836 --> 03:49.533
- Yeah, you walk up to them
and you say,

03:49.577 --> 03:53.885
"You're the Rock92 fugitive."
And wham-o!

03:53.929 --> 03:57.628
10,000 smackers just like that.
[alarm blares]

03:57.672 --> 04:01.371
- Truck 81, Squad 3,
Ambulance 61.

04:01.415 --> 04:04.505
- Okay, be back by 2:00
for the next clue.

04:04.548 --> 04:07.247
[tense music]

04:07.290 --> 04:10.380
[siren wailing]

04:24.351 --> 04:27.919
- Watch out, live wires.

04:27.963 --> 04:30.487
81 to Main,
we have a pin-in accident

04:30.531 --> 04:32.054
and downed power lines.

04:32.097 --> 04:36.363
We need the power company
to respond to this location.

04:36.406 --> 04:38.321
- Truck 81,
power company en route.

04:38.365 --> 04:40.802
ETA 15 minutes.
- Copy that.

04:40.845 --> 04:42.107
We're not waiting.

04:42.151 --> 04:43.935
Grab your rope bags,
let's corral these lines.

04:43.979 --> 04:45.241
- We're on it.

04:45.285 --> 04:46.547
- Squad extricates
when I give the all clear.

04:46.590 --> 04:47.591
- All right, copy that.

04:47.635 --> 04:49.724
Squad standby,
jaws and cutters.

04:49.767 --> 04:51.943
- Copy that.

04:51.987 --> 04:54.119
- You guys need a hand?
- It's Pelham's scene.

04:54.163 --> 04:56.426
Pelham, 37's here.

04:56.470 --> 04:57.645
- All right, great.

04:57.688 --> 04:59.429
Charge a line
to cover the driver.

04:59.473 --> 05:01.431
Let's standby
with a couple of extinguishers

05:01.475 --> 05:02.998
in case that
truck's leaking fuel.

05:03.041 --> 05:05.000
- McBride, charge a crosslay.
- Right away, Lieutenant.

05:05.043 --> 05:07.002
- Burton, Ortega,
stand by with extinguishers.

05:07.045 --> 05:08.046
- Copy that.

05:08.090 --> 05:09.309
- Gallo.
- Yeah?

05:09.352 --> 05:11.702
[electrical crackling]

05:11.746 --> 05:13.530
- Here.

05:13.574 --> 05:20.755
♪

05:20.798 --> 05:22.017
- Pull.

05:23.148 --> 05:24.628
- Yup.

05:29.198 --> 05:30.808
- Secure.
- Good.

05:30.852 --> 05:33.594
- Squad 3, move in.
- Copy that.

05:36.031 --> 05:36.945
- All yours, Lieutenant.

05:39.295 --> 05:41.558
[machinery whirring]

05:41.602 --> 05:43.386
- Severide, take cover!

05:43.430 --> 05:45.432
- Hey! Look out!

05:51.089 --> 05:54.658
- 37, get extinguishers
on those flames.

05:54.702 --> 05:55.833
- Burton, Ortega,
you heard the man.

05:55.877 --> 05:57.139
- Yes, sir!

05:59.097 --> 06:00.447
- 81, secure those lines.

06:00.490 --> 06:01.665
- Copy!

06:08.411 --> 06:09.847
- Hey, got another downed line!

06:17.377 --> 06:18.900
- Guys, come on.

06:18.943 --> 06:21.206
- Careful, that transformer
could explode again.

06:21.250 --> 06:28.388
♪

06:29.606 --> 06:31.434
- Hey, wait!

06:40.704 --> 06:41.096
.

06:41.139 --> 06:43.577
- No, no, no, no!

06:43.620 --> 06:45.622
Man down, man down!

06:45.666 --> 06:48.320
[tense music]

06:48.364 --> 06:50.061
- Watch the line,
watch the line.

06:50.105 --> 06:52.499
- Hey, McBride.

06:54.544 --> 06:56.894
McBride, can you hear me?
- What happened?

06:56.938 --> 06:59.331
- She took a direct hit
from that line.

06:59.375 --> 07:02.465
- Brett, over here!
- Go, I've got him.

07:02.509 --> 07:07.165
♪

07:07.209 --> 07:09.646
- McBride.
What happened to her?

07:09.690 --> 07:11.169
- She got zapped
by a downed line.

07:11.213 --> 07:12.170
- Where?

07:12.214 --> 07:13.345
- Hit her in the chest,
I think.

07:13.389 --> 07:14.782
- All right,
I need the heart monitor.

07:14.825 --> 07:17.524
McBride, can you hear me?
- Yeah.

07:17.567 --> 07:19.003
- Yeah? Okay, good.

07:19.047 --> 07:20.570
Can you follow my finger?

07:23.138 --> 07:25.053
Pupils are equal
but she's concussed.

07:25.096 --> 07:26.184
- All right,
she's gonna be okay.

07:26.228 --> 07:27.925
Let's give Brett some room
to work.

07:29.536 --> 07:33.017
- 61 to Main, we need a second
ambulance at this location.

07:33.061 --> 07:34.497
- Copy that.

07:34.541 --> 07:36.325
- Let's put her on the
stretcher and get her to Med.

07:36.368 --> 07:38.022
- Hey, squad,
let's pack up our gear.

07:38.066 --> 07:39.589
- Copy that.

07:50.818 --> 07:53.473
- Well, that was total mayhem.

07:53.516 --> 07:54.778
- That could've been
a lot worse.

07:54.822 --> 07:56.998
- I hope
she bounces back quick.

07:57.041 --> 07:58.390
- She wouldn't
have been in trouble

07:58.434 --> 08:00.567
if that transformer
hadn't blown out of nowhere.

08:00.610 --> 08:03.395
- I just figured the accident
caused it.

08:03.439 --> 08:04.788
- What'd you see
before it exploded?

08:04.832 --> 08:07.530
- It was smoking,
spitting fire.

08:07.574 --> 08:09.445
- I-I've seen that
with lightning strikes

08:09.489 --> 08:12.927
and flame contact, but none
of that was in play here.

08:12.970 --> 08:16.234
- Huh.
- Think it's a defective unit.

08:18.280 --> 08:21.065
- How's McBride doing?
- She was stable.

08:21.109 --> 08:22.545
A little banged up
from her fall.

08:22.589 --> 08:23.677
They have her
under observation.

08:23.720 --> 08:25.766
- I got shocked
by a bad outlet once,

08:25.809 --> 08:27.332
my arm was buzzing for days.

08:27.376 --> 08:29.596
Can't imagine what
a high-voltage line feels like.

08:29.639 --> 08:31.119
- She's pretty lucky.

08:33.991 --> 08:36.690
[rock music plays]
- We too late?

08:36.733 --> 08:38.822
- Right on time.

08:38.866 --> 08:40.302
- Enjoying the hair metal?

08:40.345 --> 08:41.999
- It's growing on me.
- [laughs]

08:42.043 --> 08:44.175
- Rock rules.
I was at Night Ranger

08:44.219 --> 08:46.264
in 1984 with my friend,
Poppers Calhoun...

08:46.308 --> 08:49.659
- Oh, Poppers?
- He had bad knees.

08:49.703 --> 08:51.574
Anyway...
- [shushes]

08:51.618 --> 08:54.316
- All right, it's 2:00 p.m.
and you know what that means.

08:54.359 --> 08:56.579
[whistle and crash]
Time for the next clue.

08:56.623 --> 08:58.929
- Well, she's an improvement
from the morning guy.

08:58.973 --> 09:00.888
- [shushes]
Silence.

09:00.931 --> 09:03.325
- [groans]
- Here we go.

09:03.368 --> 09:05.501
The fugitive will be working
for Mr. Mcgee

09:05.545 --> 09:08.112
at the five and dime,
but only part time.

09:08.156 --> 09:10.593
Got it? That's the clue.

09:12.464 --> 09:16.077
- Working with Mr. Mcgee?
What the hell does that mean?

09:16.120 --> 09:17.469
- I don't know even know
what a five and dime is.

09:17.513 --> 09:20.647
- "Raspberry Beret."
Five and dime, Mr. Mcgee...

09:20.690 --> 09:22.649
It's all in the lyrics
to "Raspberry Beret."

09:24.651 --> 09:26.217
- Even I know Prince.

09:26.261 --> 09:28.437
All right,
we got bear-ly dressed

09:28.480 --> 09:32.354
and "Raspberry Beret,"
so they're gonna have on

09:32.397 --> 09:36.663
a Bears jersey
and purple hat on their head.

09:36.706 --> 09:42.233
Okay, so if you guys go out on
a call, keep your eyes peeled.

09:42.277 --> 09:45.019
- Where are you going?
- I'm sitting on the apron

09:45.062 --> 09:47.021
with a pair of binoculars
just in case.

09:47.064 --> 09:48.196
- Oh.

09:50.677 --> 09:52.809
- Oh, hey, Kylie,
we used to have a drawer

09:52.853 --> 09:54.637
full of stuff to give away
to little visitors.

09:54.681 --> 09:56.421
- Oh, over here.

10:01.339 --> 10:03.515
I did some reorganizing.
- Ah.

10:03.559 --> 10:05.735
My two-year-old sister
is coming for a visit

10:05.779 --> 10:08.782
along with my stepdad.
Sort of, long story.

10:08.825 --> 10:11.175
- Oh, wow.
I don't know you had a sister.

10:11.219 --> 10:12.786
- Uh, yeah.

10:12.829 --> 10:15.484
I guess Amelia was born just
a little before you got here.

10:15.527 --> 10:18.443
I, um, I usually go to their
place in Rockford to visit,

10:18.487 --> 10:21.055
but with all of my trips
to see Matt,

10:21.098 --> 10:23.057
I just haven't
made it up there recently.

10:24.319 --> 10:28.715
Oh, how about...oh.

10:31.108 --> 10:34.242
This.
- Oh, look at him.

10:34.285 --> 10:37.419
With his cute, little jump bag
and badge.

10:37.462 --> 10:41.379
That's a choking hazard,
but I'm just gonna...

10:41.423 --> 10:43.033
Oh, this is perfect.
Thank you.

10:43.077 --> 10:46.080
- Yeah, you bet.
- [chuckles]

10:51.651 --> 10:55.263
- I just got a call
from CFD headquarters.

10:55.306 --> 10:57.482
I'm receiving a
Clinical Resuscitation Award

10:57.526 --> 11:01.530
for saving that newborn.
- Violet, that's fantastic.

11:01.573 --> 11:04.751
Oh, wow, Hawkins must've
been seriously impressed.

11:04.794 --> 11:07.579
That award is a huge deal.
- I guess so.

11:07.623 --> 11:09.364
- I know so.

11:11.496 --> 11:13.281
Why don't you look happy?
- [groans]

11:13.324 --> 11:15.587
I'm--I'm just surprised.
That's all.

11:15.631 --> 11:18.112
- Hmm.
Well, I'm really proud of you.

11:18.155 --> 11:20.114
We have some celebrating to do.

11:24.901 --> 11:26.903
- Hey, Chief.
- Pelham.

11:26.947 --> 11:30.472
That firefighter from 37
who got hurt on your call.

11:30.515 --> 11:33.649
- McBride, yeah.
Is there an update on her?

11:33.693 --> 11:35.520
- Separated shoulder,
mild concussion,

11:35.564 --> 11:37.740
she'll be out for a few weeks.

11:37.784 --> 11:39.524
- [sighs]
That's a tough break.

11:39.568 --> 11:41.309
- She says it's your fault.

11:43.224 --> 11:45.052
- What?
- Apparently, you ordered her

11:45.095 --> 11:46.444
to secure a live wire
on her own

11:46.488 --> 11:48.838
without the proper equipment.
- No.

11:48.882 --> 11:50.797
No way.
I never gave her that order.

11:50.840 --> 11:52.581
- That's what she says,

11:52.624 --> 11:55.062
and that's what's going
in their report.

11:55.105 --> 11:57.673
[tense music]

12:01.938 --> 12:02.112
.

12:02.156 --> 12:03.984
- She said what?

12:04.027 --> 12:06.769
- That Lieutenant Pelham
ordered her to move that wire

12:06.813 --> 12:08.597
with a pike pole.

12:10.164 --> 12:11.774
She's blaming him
for her injury.

12:11.818 --> 12:14.168
- That's crazy.
- Wow, that's...

12:14.211 --> 12:15.386
[overlapping dialogue]

12:15.430 --> 12:17.171
- Did anyone see what happened?
- Yeah.

12:17.214 --> 12:20.435
I saw her go down.
- Was she acting on orders?

12:20.478 --> 12:22.132
- Oh, well, I don't know that.

12:22.176 --> 12:23.830
- Did anyone see her
acting on orders

12:23.873 --> 12:26.397
from Pelham or otherwise?

12:26.441 --> 12:29.052
- I heard her lieutenant
put her on hose duty,

12:29.096 --> 12:31.489
but other than that...
- Medics.

12:31.533 --> 12:34.623
- We were prepping for victims.
- Behind the ambo.

12:35.929 --> 12:37.713
- It was fog of war, Chief.

12:37.757 --> 12:39.541
Power lines were
bouncing around everywhere,

12:39.584 --> 12:40.585
victims to save...

12:40.629 --> 12:44.241
[suspenseful music]

12:44.285 --> 12:47.984
- I--maybe I said something
that she misunderstood?

12:48.028 --> 12:50.770
You know,
I don't think so, but...

12:50.813 --> 12:52.641
who knows?
- Don't worry, Lieutenant.

12:52.684 --> 12:54.077
We got your back.
- Absolutely.

12:54.121 --> 12:56.166
- 100 percent.
- Don't worry about it.

12:56.210 --> 12:57.951
- He's gonna need
more than your support.

12:57.994 --> 13:00.692
He's gonna need testimonies
to contradict McBride.

13:00.736 --> 13:03.086
There's gonna be an inquiry.

13:03.130 --> 13:04.827
So I want statements
from each one of you

13:04.871 --> 13:07.917
describing exactly
what you witnessed.

13:07.961 --> 13:09.832
Engine 37 will do the same.

13:11.921 --> 13:14.141
Once we get a fuller picture
on this thing then...

13:16.839 --> 13:19.189
Maybe it'll all shake out.

13:19.233 --> 13:21.757
I want those statements
by the end of shift.

13:21.801 --> 13:22.932
all: Copy that, Chief.

13:25.282 --> 13:27.371
- Hey, this is nothing, man.
It's bureaucracy.

13:27.415 --> 13:28.677
You got this.

13:30.635 --> 13:31.898
- Kelly.

13:33.682 --> 13:37.904
So I actually know Sarah.

13:37.947 --> 13:39.383
- Yeah?
- Yeah.

13:39.427 --> 13:41.951
She volunteered for
Girls on Fire a couple times.

13:45.085 --> 13:48.479
Look, are we sure that
Pelham's in the clear on this?

13:48.523 --> 13:49.654
- Why?

13:49.698 --> 13:51.526
Did you see something
on the call?

13:51.569 --> 13:53.441
- No, but Sarah

13:53.484 --> 13:55.878
does not seem like the type
of person that would lie.

13:57.575 --> 14:01.231
- I don't know her. I know him.

14:01.275 --> 14:02.624
And he's solid.

14:02.667 --> 14:09.805
♪

14:11.938 --> 14:13.374
- You know,
I've had my differences

14:13.417 --> 14:15.767
with Pelham in the past,
but I don't question his word.

14:15.811 --> 14:19.032
- Yeah, I mean, I know there
are two sides to every story,

14:19.075 --> 14:21.817
but I'm leaning towards the one
that isn't concussed.

14:21.861 --> 14:24.167
- You better believe that's
what's going in my statement.

14:25.734 --> 14:28.041
In brighter news, did you hear
about Violet's award?

14:28.084 --> 14:29.346
- Oh, you don't have...
- That's fantastic.

14:29.390 --> 14:33.916
What award?
- For clinical resuscitation.

14:33.960 --> 14:35.309
- Hawkins gave it to her
for the baby rescue.

14:35.352 --> 14:36.832
- It's really not
that big of deal.

14:36.876 --> 14:39.008
- Yes it is.
Stop being so humble.

14:40.836 --> 14:43.099
- Congratulations.
That really is awesome.

14:46.363 --> 14:48.017
- Scott.
- [gasps]

14:48.061 --> 14:52.021
- Amelia!
Oh, I'm so happy to see you.

14:52.065 --> 14:53.283
- Sorry we're late.

14:53.327 --> 14:54.894
I tried to beat rush hour
on the Kennedy,

14:54.937 --> 14:56.069
but I guess
it's always rush hour.

14:56.112 --> 14:58.071
- Oh, my gosh,
you're getting so big.

14:58.114 --> 15:00.943
- Hi, Amelia,
welcome to Firehouse 51.

15:00.987 --> 15:02.249
You staying for long?

15:02.292 --> 15:04.033
- [stumbles]
A few days.

15:04.077 --> 15:06.079
I don't want to impose.
- Oh, are you kidding?

15:06.122 --> 15:07.428
You're gonna
have to stay longer

15:07.471 --> 15:09.343
with all the activities
I have planned for us.

15:09.386 --> 15:11.127
I'm taking them
to the Shedd Aquarium

15:11.171 --> 15:14.957
and then the nature museum
and the Adler Planetarium.

15:15.001 --> 15:16.916
Violet, you should
come with us.

15:16.959 --> 15:18.961
- Oh, count me in
for the Adler for sure.

15:19.005 --> 15:20.745
- Great!
Come on, let's go inside

15:20.789 --> 15:22.225
and check out the snacks.

15:22.269 --> 15:24.097
And I have
a little something for you.

15:24.140 --> 15:26.273
- Oh, yeah.
Wait till you see that.

15:26.316 --> 15:28.057
- [chuckles]

15:32.932 --> 15:35.978
- Had my eyes open
all the way over here

15:36.022 --> 15:39.373
and did not see
the jersey-beret combination.

15:39.416 --> 15:41.810
- There was another clue.
- What was it?

15:41.853 --> 15:45.422
- Uh, "Rapture," Debbie Harry.
- Blondie.

15:45.466 --> 15:46.858
- Oh.
- Yeah.

15:46.902 --> 15:50.210
And the fly
gets closer to the spider.

15:54.910 --> 15:56.564
- Hey.
- Hey.

16:00.481 --> 16:03.049
- Been talking to my guys,
and we're pretty sure

16:03.092 --> 16:05.529
that the wire came down
when the transformer blew.

16:05.573 --> 16:08.010
And you were dealing
with the fire at that point,

16:08.054 --> 16:11.144
so how could you
have given her that order?

16:11.187 --> 16:13.276
- Makes sense to me.
- Right.

16:15.626 --> 16:19.152
This Sarah McBride,
you guys don't have

16:19.195 --> 16:21.241
any history that
should be disclosed, do you?

16:21.284 --> 16:23.286
- I've never met her before.

16:23.330 --> 16:25.985
I have no idea
why she's gunning for me.

16:31.164 --> 16:34.167
Any further thoughts
on that transformer?

16:34.210 --> 16:36.560
- I thought I'd swing by
the scene in the morning,

16:36.604 --> 16:37.866
have another look.

16:37.909 --> 16:39.172
If there are bad
transformers out there

16:39.215 --> 16:41.826
then we need to investigate.

16:41.870 --> 16:44.046
- What's the deal
with you and OFI?

16:44.090 --> 16:45.656
You got a side gig there
or something?

16:45.700 --> 16:47.963
- [chuckles]
No.

16:48.007 --> 16:51.314
Well, kind of.
It's more like a hobby.

16:51.358 --> 16:53.012
My old man used to work arson
back in the day

16:53.055 --> 16:54.317
so I guess it's in the blood.

16:55.971 --> 16:57.059
- It's cool.

16:58.582 --> 17:00.323
Mind if I tag along?

17:00.367 --> 17:02.412
Sounds like
a welcome distraction.

17:04.675 --> 17:06.025
- You're on.

17:21.083 --> 17:24.086
- Stella,
you in physical therapy too?

17:24.130 --> 17:27.655
- No, just came by
to see how you're doing.

17:27.698 --> 17:28.699
- Really?
- Yeah.

17:28.743 --> 17:31.137
It was a pretty scary hit
you took.

17:31.180 --> 17:33.443
- Two to four weeks.
- Damn.

17:33.487 --> 17:38.013
But, hey, a few thousand volts
and you're still walking?

17:38.057 --> 17:40.885
Sarah,
you're a certified badass.

17:40.929 --> 17:42.322
- Maybe.

17:45.499 --> 17:49.068
- Yeah, I heard you're saying
our new lieutenant's at fault.

17:49.111 --> 17:51.722
[apprehensive music]

17:51.766 --> 17:53.072
- Yeah.

17:53.115 --> 17:55.813
Well, gotta do
what I gotta do, you know?

17:55.857 --> 17:57.902
- Oh, yeah, no.
I get it.

17:57.946 --> 18:02.168
Hey, I'm not here
to give you a hard time.

18:02.211 --> 18:05.258
You know, I mean,
Pelham seems like a good guy,

18:05.301 --> 18:09.653
but like I said, he's new.
So...

18:12.178 --> 18:14.267
Yeah, what happened?

18:14.310 --> 18:16.312
- It's all in
the incident report.

18:16.356 --> 18:19.228
- Oh, I know.
It's just...

18:19.272 --> 18:22.405
those things are
so dry and procedural.

18:22.449 --> 18:24.929
I was hoping to get
the full story from you.

18:24.973 --> 18:28.063
- Well, that's what's
in the report, the full story.

18:29.456 --> 18:31.501
- Okay.

18:31.545 --> 18:33.242
I--I'm just trying
to figure out

18:33.286 --> 18:36.115
what he could've seen
from his position.

18:36.158 --> 18:38.726
You know, did he see
the line go down?

18:38.769 --> 18:40.293
- I guess so because he just

18:40.336 --> 18:42.643
pointed at me
and gave the order.

18:42.686 --> 18:45.559
- Whoa, hey, Sarah, I am just
trying to get clarification.

18:45.602 --> 18:47.169
- I've said all
I have to say on that.

18:47.213 --> 18:53.393
♪

19:04.969 --> 19:05.144
.

19:05.187 --> 19:07.146
- How's it going?

19:07.189 --> 19:10.758
Firefighters of the CFD,
we were here on the scene.

19:10.801 --> 19:12.368
You have any idea
why this thing blew?

19:12.412 --> 19:13.804
- Well, if you were
on the scene,

19:13.848 --> 19:15.589
you knew that a moving van
slammed into it, right?

19:15.632 --> 19:17.852
- Yeah, but the pole survived.

19:17.895 --> 19:19.854
Shouldn't the transformer
have held steady?

19:19.897 --> 19:21.638
- Look, I'm just here
to replace the thing.

19:23.031 --> 19:25.468
- How much oil goes
into one of these things?

19:25.512 --> 19:28.471
- Unit this size?
50 gallons.

19:28.515 --> 19:29.777
- Huh.

19:29.820 --> 19:31.300
Well, since you already
pulled it down,

19:31.344 --> 19:32.997
do you mind if we take it?

19:33.041 --> 19:35.261
I'd like to show it to the
Office of Fire Investigation.

19:35.304 --> 19:37.350
- Save me a trip
to the scrap yard.

19:37.393 --> 19:38.525
Have at it.

19:42.398 --> 19:43.834
- Want to give me a hand?

19:44.705 --> 19:47.664
[pensive music]

19:47.708 --> 19:49.927
♪

19:49.971 --> 19:51.059
What is it?

19:52.974 --> 19:55.759
- This is where I was standing
when that thing exploded.

19:55.803 --> 19:58.806
Truck 81 was parked
right about there.

19:58.849 --> 20:02.418
And she was on the other side,
near 37,

20:02.462 --> 20:06.117
which means there was
no sightline.

20:06.161 --> 20:08.816
So how could I have
given her a verbal command?

20:10.731 --> 20:13.603
- I believe you, 100%.

20:13.647 --> 20:16.127
- [sighs]
But you can't confirm it.

20:16.171 --> 20:18.782
- Hey, in my experience
with the pencil pushers

20:18.826 --> 20:20.306
at the board of the review,

20:20.349 --> 20:22.133
they'll never know what
it's like to be on the ground.

20:23.744 --> 20:25.093
So your best bet
is to keep your head down,

20:25.136 --> 20:26.921
do your job,
and let the chips fall.

20:28.314 --> 20:32.143
- I get that, but given
my disciplinary record,

20:32.187 --> 20:34.015
it's not chips
that are gonna fall.

20:36.017 --> 20:36.974
It's an axe.

20:38.715 --> 20:41.240
Come on,
let's load this thing up.

20:44.721 --> 20:47.202
- Hey.
[gasps]

20:47.246 --> 20:49.813
Wow.
[chuckles]

20:49.857 --> 20:52.816
I cannot believe
how fast she's growing.

20:52.860 --> 20:54.949
- This is a really fun age.

20:54.992 --> 20:58.822
So curious about
everything and fast.

20:58.866 --> 21:00.781
Don't blink or she'll be
in the shark section.

21:00.824 --> 21:02.130
- I have to take a video
for Matt

21:02.173 --> 21:04.088
so he can see
how much she's changed.

21:04.132 --> 21:06.352
- How are things going
with all that?

21:06.395 --> 21:10.704
Portland and the long distance.
- Um, it's fine.

21:10.747 --> 21:13.663
I mean, it's amazing
when we're together,

21:13.707 --> 21:16.013
but it's never long enough.

21:16.057 --> 21:18.973
I'm taking another furlough
soon and so is Matt.

21:19.016 --> 21:20.279
- Matt.

21:21.584 --> 21:23.412
- Did she just...
- Oh, yeah.

21:23.456 --> 21:26.546
She's been saying his name ever
since your last visit together.

21:26.589 --> 21:28.548
[soft sentimental music]

21:28.591 --> 21:32.160
- You remember this guy?
- Matt.

21:32.203 --> 21:39.123
♪

21:42.257 --> 21:44.215
- All eyewitness statements
are in

21:44.259 --> 21:46.653
from all four companies
that were present at the scene.

21:46.696 --> 21:48.089
- And?

21:48.132 --> 21:51.179
- None of them can back up
Sarah McBride's account,

21:51.222 --> 21:53.877
but they don't
contradict her either.

21:53.921 --> 21:55.662
- Chief,

21:55.705 --> 21:58.142
Severide and I were back
on the scene yesterday.

21:58.186 --> 21:59.883
And just looking
at how it all laid out...

21:59.927 --> 22:02.886
[scoffs]
I've never been more sure.

22:02.930 --> 22:04.714
I couldn't have even seen her
when that wire came down.

22:04.758 --> 22:07.238
- I don't doubt you, Pelham.

22:07.282 --> 22:10.024
There's a review board that
weighs up all the evidence.

22:10.067 --> 22:13.244
- It'll turn into
a "he said, she said."

22:19.512 --> 22:21.514
- I went to talk to McBride.

22:21.557 --> 22:23.385
- What? When?

22:23.429 --> 22:24.560
- Off shift.

22:24.604 --> 22:27.607
[apprehensive music]

22:27.650 --> 22:30.261
I know her some.
Girls on Fire stuff.

22:30.305 --> 22:32.176
- You talk about the accident?
- Mm-hmm.

22:34.004 --> 22:36.790
I can't explain it, but, um,

22:36.833 --> 22:38.269
yeah, I got a weird hit
off her.

22:38.313 --> 22:41.011
- What kind of hit?
- Defensive.

22:42.796 --> 22:44.580
I don't want to accuse her
of anything,

22:44.624 --> 22:46.800
but something's not right.

22:52.806 --> 22:54.373
[knock on door]

22:55.939 --> 22:57.376
- Lieutenant Severide?
- Yep.

22:57.419 --> 23:00.422
- Captain Van Meter
is on the apparatus floor.

23:00.466 --> 23:01.641
- Go.

23:07.342 --> 23:09.866
- Supposedly this thing
had 50 gallons of oil in it

23:09.910 --> 23:12.782
when it blew, but if that
was true, I wouldn't be here.

23:12.826 --> 23:16.830
I'd be in the burn ward.
It was half-full at most.

23:16.873 --> 23:19.876
- So you're saying the accident
wouldn't have caused it to blow

23:19.920 --> 23:21.443
except that most of
the coolant had evaporated?

23:21.487 --> 23:24.141
- Makes sense, right?
- Judging by the serial number,

23:24.185 --> 23:25.752
this thing is 10 years
past its due date.

23:25.795 --> 23:27.318
- Probably cutting costs

23:27.362 --> 23:29.799
by letting them run longer
than they should.

23:29.843 --> 23:31.801
Well, maybe I can subpoena

23:31.845 --> 23:32.976
the power company
for their records?

23:33.020 --> 23:35.196
Pressure them
into replacing them all

23:35.239 --> 23:38.155
or face criminal charges.
It's nice work, Severide.

23:39.635 --> 23:42.812
Seager's gonna be upset
you solved one without her.

23:42.856 --> 23:44.684
You two did great work
in those church fires,

23:44.727 --> 23:46.033
but now she keeps bugging me

23:46.076 --> 23:47.513
about bringing you back
on other cases.

23:47.556 --> 23:48.992
- [chuckles]

23:49.036 --> 23:51.168
You did remind her
I don't work for OFI, right?

23:51.212 --> 23:52.822
- Yeah, she didn't care.
- [laughs]

23:52.866 --> 23:55.129
- She says it's no fun burning
the midnight oil without you.

23:59.873 --> 24:01.178
- Hey, Violet.
- Hmm?

24:01.222 --> 24:02.441
- This just came
for you from headquarters.

24:02.484 --> 24:04.225
- Thanks, Kylie.

24:07.228 --> 24:09.665
- You're not gonna open that?

24:09.709 --> 24:12.276
- Uh, yeah.
Yes, I guess I should.

24:15.192 --> 24:18.500
- Violet, you won an award?

24:18.544 --> 24:20.937
- For clinical resuscitation.
- You knew?

24:20.981 --> 24:22.373
- I figured she told you.

24:22.417 --> 24:26.073
- And there's a little note
from Chief Hawkins.

24:27.640 --> 24:29.772
- What's it say?
- Um.

24:29.816 --> 24:31.382
"Keep up the great work.

24:31.426 --> 24:33.341
"This is one of
many more to come,

24:33.384 --> 24:34.473
I'm sure of it."

24:34.516 --> 24:36.213
- That's what
I'm talking about, V.

24:36.257 --> 24:37.214
Congrats.

24:37.258 --> 24:39.129
- Thanks, Ritter.
- Yeah.

24:39.173 --> 24:40.870
- Better put this
in my locker.

24:42.698 --> 24:44.047
- Way to go, Violet.

24:44.091 --> 24:46.354
- Thanks.
[chuckles]

24:53.056 --> 24:54.580
- What do we know
about this guy, Hawkins?

24:54.623 --> 24:56.233
- What do you mean?

24:56.277 --> 24:59.541
- Well, I mean, we all know
Violet's a great medic.

24:59.585 --> 25:01.587
And I'm not saying
she doesn't deserve an award.

25:01.630 --> 25:03.327
- Okay, good.

25:03.371 --> 25:05.199
- But the last
paramedic field chief,

25:05.242 --> 25:08.245
he came by 51, what?
Every six months?

25:08.289 --> 25:10.987
And this guy here
is working shifts with Violet

25:11.031 --> 25:13.816
and giving her awards,
writing cute, little notes.

25:13.860 --> 25:16.689
I mean, isn't it obvious?

25:16.732 --> 25:18.952
He has ulterior motives.

25:20.867 --> 25:23.347
- Or maybe you're reacting
this way because

25:23.391 --> 25:25.959
you have feelings for her
and you blew it?

25:26.002 --> 25:30.790
- No, no, it's just wrong.
I mean, he's her boss.

25:34.620 --> 25:36.883
[alarm blares]

25:36.926 --> 25:38.841
- Ambulance 61,
person in distress.

25:38.885 --> 25:40.582
3613 East State.

25:40.626 --> 25:43.585
[tense music]

25:43.629 --> 25:44.978
- Get it off me.

25:45.021 --> 25:46.719
- Hey, I'm the one
that called you.

25:46.762 --> 25:47.894
It's my neighbor.

25:50.026 --> 25:51.854
- [screams]
Get it off!

25:51.898 --> 25:54.204
Get it off me.
Get it off me.

25:54.248 --> 25:56.511
[screams]
Get it off.

25:59.862 --> 26:00.080
.

26:00.123 --> 26:01.951
- Get it off me.
- Sir, we're paramedics.

26:01.995 --> 26:03.126
Can you tell us what's wrong?

26:03.170 --> 26:04.388
- He's been like this
for 20 minutes.

26:04.432 --> 26:05.694
- What's on you, Travis?
We can't see.

26:05.738 --> 26:07.609
- [sobbing]
It's in here.

26:07.653 --> 26:10.394
- Any history of drug abuse
or psychiatric issues?

26:10.438 --> 26:11.613
- Not that I know of.

26:11.657 --> 26:13.267
I mean,
he's a pretty chill guy.

26:13.310 --> 26:15.443
- Travis, we need you to stop
moving so we can take a look.

26:15.486 --> 26:17.576
- I can't stop
or it gets worse.

26:17.619 --> 26:20.666
[crying]

26:20.709 --> 26:23.451
- Hey...
- Come on, buddy.

26:23.494 --> 26:25.584
- Easy.
- [groans] No, don't!

26:25.627 --> 26:27.324
- She can't help you
if you don't stay still.

26:27.368 --> 26:29.413
- It's moving everywhere.

26:29.457 --> 26:30.893
- Okay, grab me the amio.

26:30.937 --> 26:32.591
- You think he's going
into cardiac arrest?

26:32.634 --> 26:34.331
- It's not for him.

26:34.375 --> 26:40.773
♪

26:40.816 --> 26:41.774
Thank you.

26:44.603 --> 26:47.736
- No, no...
- Here you go.

26:47.780 --> 26:49.782
- [screams]
What the hell?

26:55.048 --> 26:57.354
It's slowing down. It stopped.

26:57.398 --> 27:01.097
[chuckles]
It stopped.

27:01.141 --> 27:03.622
- Okay, Travis, can you
lay on your left side for me?

27:08.975 --> 27:10.019
- What happened?

27:10.063 --> 27:11.586
- I paralyzed
whatever's in there

27:11.630 --> 27:13.370
with a shot of amiodarone.

27:14.676 --> 27:17.287
- Ooh.
You want to do this part?

27:17.331 --> 27:18.985
- Not a chance.

27:19.028 --> 27:25.774
♪

27:26.906 --> 27:28.995
- Oh.

27:29.038 --> 27:30.126
- Oh!

27:30.170 --> 27:31.475
- [yelps]

27:39.832 --> 27:42.617
- That was revolting,
and you were incredible.

27:44.924 --> 27:47.187
- I think maybe
I got that award because

27:47.230 --> 27:53.062
some feelings have developed
between me and Hawkins.

27:53.106 --> 27:55.021
- Did something happen?

27:55.064 --> 27:56.979
- Oh, my God, no.

27:57.023 --> 27:58.372
I just...

27:59.634 --> 28:02.855
There was a vibe.

28:02.898 --> 28:05.771
- Violet, you're a great medic.

28:05.814 --> 28:09.165
I mean, you just proved it in
there for the umpteenth time.

28:09.209 --> 28:13.213
You should feel really proud of
yourself for saving that baby.

28:13.256 --> 28:14.693
And you deserve that award.

28:16.564 --> 28:18.958
- Okay.
- [chuckles]

28:23.223 --> 28:25.834
[knock on door]
- Stewart.

28:25.878 --> 28:29.838
Now a good time?
- Hey, Chief Boden.

28:29.882 --> 28:32.232
What brings you
to the West Side?

28:32.275 --> 28:35.191
- Pelham inquiry.
- Oh, okay.

28:35.235 --> 28:36.627
Make a decision about that yet?

28:36.671 --> 28:38.542
- No, not yet,
but before they do,

28:38.586 --> 28:41.763
I wanted to get
your take on something.

28:41.807 --> 28:44.548
Sarah McBride,
tell me all about her.

28:44.592 --> 28:47.900
- Good kid.
Hate to have her on the bench.

28:47.943 --> 28:51.077
- So you're a fan.
- Oh, yeah.

28:51.120 --> 28:53.035
She's a little green maybe.

28:53.079 --> 28:56.256
A little on the quiet side,
but hard worker.

28:56.299 --> 28:57.997
- Is she honest?

28:58.040 --> 29:00.564
- In my experience,
yes, very.

29:02.523 --> 29:04.351
You know, it's funny,
for a nobody,

29:04.394 --> 29:06.570
she is sure getting
a lot of attention this week.

29:06.614 --> 29:10.009
You're the second DDC
to ask about her.

29:10.052 --> 29:12.620
- Who was the first?
- Chief Kilbourne.

29:15.579 --> 29:18.495
- Did Kilbourne call you?

29:18.539 --> 29:20.497
- Yeah,
right after the accident.

29:20.541 --> 29:23.065
Wanted to know all about her.

29:23.109 --> 29:25.372
- Before she filed
her accusation?

29:25.415 --> 29:28.201
- I think so.

29:28.244 --> 29:31.682
- You think so or yeah?

29:31.726 --> 29:34.816
[tense music]

29:34.860 --> 29:38.602
- You know, honestly,
I can't say for sure.

29:38.646 --> 29:40.779
It sounds like something

29:40.822 --> 29:43.172
you ought to be taking up
directly with Chief Kilbourne.

29:46.349 --> 29:49.265
- Of course it's okay.
It's part of our training.

29:49.309 --> 29:50.919
No. It'll be okay.

29:50.963 --> 29:53.879
- We're not gonna do that.
- He'll understand.

29:53.922 --> 29:56.185
- What's going on?
- Do you think Boden

29:56.229 --> 29:59.667
would let us all take the rigs
out for driver's training

29:59.710 --> 30:02.670
around downtown
until we find the fugitive?

30:02.713 --> 30:04.846
- Boden's got a lieutenant
on the ropes.

30:04.890 --> 30:06.456
We need to be
showing our support,

30:06.500 --> 30:08.284
not asking for dumb favors.

30:08.328 --> 30:10.634
- God himself could not
persuade Boden to take our rigs

30:10.678 --> 30:12.462
out of our districts
for a radio contest.

30:12.506 --> 30:14.290
[alarm blares]

30:14.334 --> 30:17.728
- Engine 51, vehicle fire.
500 West Clark Street.

30:17.772 --> 30:20.209
- Downtown.
- God himself. Hmm.

30:23.082 --> 30:26.041
[sirens wailing]

30:26.085 --> 30:32.700
♪

30:36.486 --> 30:38.880
- Hermann.
- Hey, Dorcester.

30:38.924 --> 30:41.100
We got called
for a vehicle fire.

30:41.143 --> 30:42.884
- No fire but
a hell of a lot of glass.

30:44.581 --> 30:45.669
I could use some help
with the cleanup,

30:45.713 --> 30:46.757
if you don't mind?
- Yeah.

30:46.801 --> 30:48.847
All right,
grab the brooms, boys.

30:48.890 --> 30:50.500
We're gonna help
sweep up the street.

30:50.544 --> 30:53.547
Back up, people, back up.
All right, let us do our work.

30:53.590 --> 30:55.418
Back up, people,
back up, please.

30:55.462 --> 30:57.029
- Can I just cross the street?

30:57.072 --> 31:00.641
- No, ma'am, let us do our job.
Just stay on the sidewalk.

31:00.684 --> 31:02.251
- Okay, I'll just stand
right here then.

31:04.384 --> 31:08.083
- Uh, are you
the Rock92ThePanther fugitive?

31:08.127 --> 31:09.955
- Yes, I am.

31:09.998 --> 31:12.522
You won $10,000.
- What?

31:12.566 --> 31:15.177
Oh, my God, I can't believe it.

31:15.221 --> 31:18.354
I actually only heard one clue,
Bears jersey.

31:18.398 --> 31:19.790
[laughter]

31:19.834 --> 31:22.489
And here you were,
right in front of me.

31:22.532 --> 31:24.360
- Congratulations.
What's your name?

31:24.404 --> 31:26.406
- Roger, Roger Fischer.

31:26.449 --> 31:28.799
[laughter]

31:36.590 --> 31:37.765
- Chief Kilbourne.

31:39.941 --> 31:40.899
- Boden.

31:42.552 --> 31:45.381
How are you?
- On the war path.

31:45.425 --> 31:47.731
- Wow, okay.

31:51.300 --> 31:57.002
- I already know you're
not happy I hired Jason Pelham.

31:57.045 --> 31:59.787
And now a firefighter
in your district

31:59.830 --> 32:02.355
levelled serious
allegations against him.

32:02.398 --> 32:04.792
- You think I had something
to do with that?

32:04.835 --> 32:07.490
- I think you saw
an opportunity and you jumped.

32:07.534 --> 32:11.886
I think you found that young
woman in a vulnerable state,

32:11.930 --> 32:15.803
and you pressured her
into fabricating a story.

32:15.846 --> 32:18.414
What firefighter
is gonna say "no"

32:18.458 --> 32:20.025
to a deputy district chief?

32:22.984 --> 32:26.031
- That is one hell
of an accusation, Boden.

32:26.074 --> 32:29.686
- Can you deny it?
- Can you prove it?

32:33.081 --> 32:35.649
Let me float
an alternate theory.

32:37.303 --> 32:40.001
Pelham screwed the pooch,

32:40.045 --> 32:42.961
and now you're desperate
to find someone else to blame

32:43.004 --> 32:45.659
for your lousy hiring decision.

32:47.182 --> 32:50.881
I told you Pelham was bad news.

32:50.925 --> 32:52.622
This is on you.

32:52.666 --> 32:58.324
♪

33:02.545 --> 33:02.763
.

33:02.806 --> 33:04.460
- How do we prove it?

33:04.504 --> 33:07.202
- How can we?
Unless she fesses up.

33:07.246 --> 33:08.812
Look, Pelham, I understand

33:08.856 --> 33:13.121
why you took the hit
to protect Captain Stafford,

33:13.165 --> 33:15.558
but Kilbourne clearly
has it in for you.

33:15.602 --> 33:17.778
Don't it seem like it's time...

33:17.821 --> 33:19.388
[suspenseful music]

33:19.432 --> 33:23.392
To tell me the full story
of why you slugged his friend?

33:23.436 --> 33:25.003
- Kilbourne knew as well
as anyone that Stafford

33:25.046 --> 33:27.222
was in a tailspin, he just
figured he'd pull out of it.

33:27.266 --> 33:29.746
I was less optimistic.

33:29.790 --> 33:33.141
I could tell Stafford was gonna
end up getting someone killed.

33:34.490 --> 33:36.405
My only crime was not following

33:36.449 --> 33:38.451
the old school code
of turning a blind eye.

33:40.801 --> 33:44.674
I am the pissant lieutenant
who forced his buddy to retire.

33:46.633 --> 33:50.550
That is why Kilbourne
will never forgive me.

33:53.466 --> 33:56.512
- Well, that was
a big waste of time.

33:56.556 --> 33:58.688
- Nah, it built camaraderie.

33:58.732 --> 34:00.429
You know, which is something
you have to do as a leader.

34:00.473 --> 34:01.909
- Uh-huh.
- Yeah.

34:01.952 --> 34:05.217
And we're gonna need that
camaraderie as we get ready

34:05.260 --> 34:08.437
for the Kiss104
Hands on a Hummer challenge.

34:08.481 --> 34:09.482
- Don't want to know
what that is.

34:09.525 --> 34:11.788
- Yeah, you see,
they have a Hummer

34:11.832 --> 34:14.095
that's driving down the street
at two miles an hour,

34:14.139 --> 34:16.271
and if you can keep pace
with the thing

34:16.315 --> 34:18.621
and hold on
as long as you can...

34:20.145 --> 34:21.929
- Hey, you.

34:21.972 --> 34:24.149
I figured you'd be
halfway to Rockford by now.

34:24.192 --> 34:26.977
- Well, Amelia wanted
one last goodbye.

34:27.021 --> 34:29.589
- Sylbie.
- Oh.

34:29.632 --> 34:32.113
[groans]

34:32.157 --> 34:34.202
I miss you already,
little lady bug.

34:34.246 --> 34:36.465
I'm gonna come and
see you real soon, okay?

34:36.509 --> 34:39.468
- Actually, I was thinking
we'd come down

34:39.512 --> 34:40.817
to the city
a little more often.

34:40.861 --> 34:42.993
I know how busy you are,
and I think

34:43.037 --> 34:45.126
it's good for you to go
see Matt as much as possible.

34:45.170 --> 34:47.650
- Oh, well, I can do both.

34:47.694 --> 34:50.175
I promise it won't be
so long next time.

34:54.004 --> 34:56.572
- When Julie and I
first started dating,

34:56.616 --> 34:58.792
I had a lot of business travel.

34:58.835 --> 35:01.403
Carving our time together
was hard, but we made it work.

35:01.447 --> 35:04.058
[sentimental music]

35:04.102 --> 35:05.712
I look back now...

35:08.062 --> 35:09.368
And I wish...

35:11.196 --> 35:14.808
Just one more movie night
on the couch

35:14.851 --> 35:17.724
or that ski trip to Boyne
we kept meaning to take.

35:19.378 --> 35:20.857
My hope for you?

35:22.381 --> 35:25.210
That you get as much time
as possible with Matt.

35:27.342 --> 35:30.650
So we'll come to you
for a little while.

35:30.693 --> 35:31.781
Deal?

35:34.349 --> 35:35.655
- Deal.

35:43.271 --> 35:44.751
- Violet.

35:44.794 --> 35:47.232
- Sorry to just walk in.
Your assistant isn't out there.

35:47.275 --> 35:48.798
- No worries.
Come on in.

35:51.932 --> 35:54.761
- The award, it's a real honor.
- Well, that baby wouldn't be

35:54.804 --> 35:56.719
with his parents right now
if it wasn't for you.

35:56.763 --> 35:59.244
- And you.
We did it together.

36:03.465 --> 36:05.163
- You don't think
you deserve it?

36:05.206 --> 36:10.472
- I--I don't know.
I mean, maybe?

36:10.516 --> 36:15.260
- Violet, there's no maybe.
You do.

36:15.303 --> 36:18.437
- Okay, so it's not
like you have...

36:20.395 --> 36:24.225
Feelings for me
or anything like that?

36:24.269 --> 36:25.574
Right?

36:27.141 --> 36:28.360
- Well, I...

36:31.363 --> 36:32.538
Um...

36:34.192 --> 36:35.541
I don't let personal issues

36:35.584 --> 36:37.804
affect my decision making
at work.

36:40.328 --> 36:44.985
- Okay, okay.
Good.

36:45.028 --> 36:47.335
Well, then, thank you.

36:47.379 --> 36:53.994
♪

36:56.301 --> 36:57.824
- But I...

37:00.479 --> 37:02.263
I think we should
make an effort

37:02.307 --> 37:05.875
to stay away from each other.
At least for a while.

37:08.530 --> 37:11.316
- That's a really,
really good idea.

37:33.642 --> 37:35.949
- We gonna order in?
- Sure.

37:38.256 --> 37:40.867
- Hey, what's going on?

37:45.045 --> 37:46.699
You were quiet
the whole ride home.

37:49.441 --> 37:51.138
- How come you never
mentioned anything

37:51.181 --> 37:54.881
about working that
big case with Seager?

37:54.924 --> 37:56.056
- You serious?

37:56.099 --> 37:58.580
- I just think it's odd
that you never--

37:58.624 --> 38:00.669
you never brought it up once.

38:02.584 --> 38:05.239
- I'm sure I would've
if you picked up my calls.

38:05.283 --> 38:07.110
[solemn music]

38:07.154 --> 38:09.548
- I'm sorry.
- I know.

38:14.117 --> 38:15.467
- I can't help but feel like

38:15.510 --> 38:17.686
maybe you can't
totally forgive me.

38:17.730 --> 38:21.603
- You apologized.
I accepted it.

38:21.647 --> 38:23.692
You're the one
who won't let it go.

38:29.176 --> 38:32.962
- I let you--I let you down
and I let Boden down.

38:33.006 --> 38:35.965
- You explained it to us.
You explained it.

38:36.009 --> 38:37.663
You need time
to figure things out.

38:45.279 --> 38:46.628
No one is perfect.

38:52.155 --> 38:54.027
Not even Stella Kidd.

38:59.598 --> 39:01.774
- Maybe I just...

39:07.475 --> 39:10.609
I really want to be
the perfect one for you.

39:10.652 --> 39:17.790
♪

39:31.325 --> 39:32.631
- [mumbles]

39:35.329 --> 39:36.548
- You...

39:38.811 --> 39:40.203
Are the perfect one for me.

39:47.863 --> 39:50.997
[apprehensive music]

39:51.040 --> 39:57.960
♪

40:02.051 --> 40:03.488
- Chief.

40:12.758 --> 40:14.977
- They finished reviewing
your case.

40:20.722 --> 40:22.550
- Want a beer?

40:22.594 --> 40:24.030
- Yup.

40:31.559 --> 40:32.691
- All right.

40:36.434 --> 40:39.785
How bad is it?

40:39.828 --> 40:42.178
- They recommending
termination.

40:42.222 --> 40:49.142
♪

40:58.064 --> 40:59.326
- [screams]

41:20.260 --> 41:23.219
[dramatic music]

41:23.263 --> 41:30.183
♪

41:50.290 --> 41:53.206
[wolf howls]
